<Class name="CnEcHubble" id="d4ee37f2-44f4-43a3-8f53-bc1ce91f57cf">
    <superclass name="CnEcExtractLoad"/>
    <transient/>
    <persistentAllowed/>
    <sharedTransientAllowed/>
    <subclassPersistentAllowed/>
    <subclassSharedTransientAllowed/>
    <subclassTransientAllowed/>
    <transientAllowed/>
    <text>___________________________________________________________________________

              P R O P R I E T A R Y   N O T I C E

This software, in whole and in every part, is proprietary to Jade Software
Corporation Limited at Christchurch, New Zealand and is not to be
reproduced, used or disclosed except upon prior written permission of Jade
Software Corporation Limited.

  COPYRIGHT © JADE SOFTWARE CORPORATION LIMITED 2004 - ALL RIGHTS RESERVED
____________________________________________________________________________

	Rules:

    1/. First Tag must be object class name.

    2/. No output from any single object may contain a tag of the same signature as the object identifying tag.
    	i.e. If the object is a 'Product' no other tag of &lt;Product&gt; may exist within the definition of the 'Product'.
    	Any references to another 'Product' should be made via the 'oid' Tag, and simply contain the getOidString.

	3/. The XML output string from the extract will not 'by default be visible' within an XML browser, as it may not have an
		'all encompassing' Tag.  It will instead be made up of a series of top level tags, where each one represents another object

	4/. For importing,
		Tag of &lt;oid&gt; is required for all objects being created.
		Tag of &lt;OID&gt; is required for all references and Suppress Tag value must be set for the referenced class so that the
		Class name on referenced classes is not shown. An example of a Role within one of these files follows:

		&lt;Role&gt;
		    &lt;oid&gt;2768.289&lt;/oid&gt;
		    &lt;allPermissions&gt;
		        &lt;OID&gt;2910.79&lt;/OID&gt;
		        &lt;OID&gt;2910.78&lt;/OID&gt;
		        &lt;OID&gt;2910.51&lt;/OID&gt;
		        &lt;OID&gt;2910.50&lt;/OID&gt;
		        &lt;OID&gt;2910.10&lt;/OID&gt;
		    &lt;/allPermissions&gt;
		    &lt;allRoles&gt;&lt;/allRoles&gt;
		    &lt;code&gt;Staff Manager&lt;/code&gt;
		    &lt;description&gt;Staff Manager&lt;/description&gt;
		    &lt;narrative&gt;&lt;/narrative&gt;
		    &lt;permissions&gt;&lt;/permissions&gt;
		    &lt;myOrgIfPrimaryRole&gt;
		        &lt;OID&gt;2778.2434&lt;/OID&gt;
		    &lt;/myOrgIfPrimaryRole&gt;
		    &lt;myOrganisation&gt;
		        &lt;OID&gt;2778.2434&lt;/OID&gt;
		    &lt;/myOrganisation&gt;
		&lt;/Role&gt;
		
	5/. If doing partial imports, NOIDs may be put into a seperate file and processed first.  A NOID establishes a reference
		to an object that already exists in the system that you are importing into.  In the example in 4/. above,
		the myOrganisation may already exist in the system. example a/. below tells the system that if it can find an Organisation
		within the new system that has an 'orgCode' of 'Freds Emporium' that it should use that. If it can't find one, then it
		should present a list of all Organisations in a listBox for the user to select from. The value displayed for each of the
		objects within the list box should be 'orgCode', and a seperate text box should display 'Freds Emporium', so that the User
		knows what they are attempting to substitue for. 
		
		example a/.
		&lt;Organisation&gt;
    		&lt;NOID&gt;
				&lt;DISPLAY_PROPERTY&gt;orgCode&lt;/DISPLAY_PROPERTY&gt;
				&lt;DISPLAY_VALUE&gt;Freds Emporium&lt;/DISPLAY_VALUE&gt;        
    		&lt;/NOID&gt;
    		&lt;oid&gt;2778.2434&lt;/oid&gt;
		&lt;/Organisation&gt;
		
		While example a/. is the recommended approach...
		The following alternative may be used when the OID of the object in the new system is already known. ( DISPLAY_PROPERTY
		optional, in this example and is the 'belt and braces' answer for when the OID doesn't exist. Oops...)
		
		example b/.
		&lt;Organisation&gt;
    		&lt;NOID&gt;
				&lt;OID&gt;2778.1&lt;/OID&gt;
				&lt;DISPLAY_PROPERTY&gt;orgCode&lt;/DISPLAY_PROPERTY&gt;        
    		&lt;/NOID&gt;
    		&lt;oid&gt;2778.2434&lt;/oid&gt;
		&lt;/Organisation&gt;
		
	6/. Exporting. 
		Having initialised a Huble with the noidFileName and outputFileName set, along with the mandatory
		"Default Full Attribute", an empty oidTableRoot, and an ObjectArray containing the objects that you wish to export, the export
		method will create the appropraitely formatted files to use the ouput to load into another system. The NOID format used is
		the one in example a/. of section 5/. above.
		Any objects that are to be referenced via NOID must have a 'cnEcNoid' method re-implemented on their class for the export method
		to use.</text>
